A NullPointerException is thrown when your code attempts to use a null reference where an object instance was expected. Here are some common causes of NullPointerExceptions and ways you might be able to resolve them:

1. **Uninitialized Objects** - You may try to access methods or properties on an uninitialized object. For example:

    ```java
    Car myCar; // This is null by default, it hasn't been initialized.
    System.out.println(myCar.getMake()); // This would cause a NullPointerException because myCar is null.
    ```
   To solve this issue you should initialize the object before trying to use its methods:

    ```java
    Car myCar = new Car();
    System.out.println(myCar.getMake()); // Now it's OK, as long as getMake() doesn't itself access a member of myCar that hasn't been initialized yet.
    ```

2. **Null values in Collections** - Null values can also cause exceptions. For example:

    ```java
    List<String> strings = new ArrayList<>();
    strings.add("Hello");
    strings.add(null); // This is a valid operation in Java.
    for (String string : strings) {
        System.out.println(string.length()); // This would cause a NullPointerException if it encountered a null element.
    }
    ```
   To prevent this, you should either ensure that you don't add null values to your collection or handle the possibility of a null value in your loops:

    ```java
    List<String> strings = new ArrayList<>();
    strings.add("Hello");
    for (String string : strings) {
        if(string != null){
            System.out.println(string.length()); // This would not cause a NullPointerException now.
        }
    }
    ```

3. **Accessing methods on a null object** - You can also get a NullPointerException when trying to access a method on a null reference:

    ```java
    String s = null;
    System.out.println(s.length()); // This would cause a NullPointerException because length() is being invoked on a null reference.
    ```
   To prevent this, make sure that you're not invoking methods or accessing properties on an object that may be null:

    ```java
    String s = "Hello"; // It's safe now as we have initialized 's'.
    System.out.println(s.length()); // Now it's OK.
    ```

Remember, you should always check if a reference is `null` before trying to use its methods or access its properties:

```java
if (myObject != null) {
    myObject.doSomething();
}
```

