Inheritance is a key aspect of Object Oriented Programming (OOP) which allows us to define a class in terms of another class, which makes it easier to create and maintain an application. This also provides the opportunity to reuse the code. 

Java and Python both support inheritance but they handle it slightly differently:

1. In Java, classes are always explicitly derived from the base class using the `extends` keyword. Multiple inheritances (a class extending more than one superclass) is not supported by Java. 

Example in Java:
```java
public class Animal { //base class
    public void eat() {
        System.out.println("Eating...");
    }
}

public class Dog extends Animal { // derived class
    public void bark(){
       System.out.println("Barking...");
    }
}
```
