 The quicksort algorithm is a sorting algorithm that works by selecting a "pivot" element from the array and partitioning the rest of the elements into two groups, according to whether they are less than or greater than the pivot. This process is repeated recursively until the entire array is sorted. 

Here is an implementation of the quicksort algorithm in Python:

```python
def quick_sort(arr):
 if len(arr) <= 1:
 return arr # base case - only need to partition the array once
 else:
 pivot = arr[0]
 for i in range(1, len(arr)):
 subarray = arr[:i]
 subarray.append(pivot)
 if i > 0:
 subarray[i-1] = arr[i-1]
 pivot_index = i
 return subarray

def partition(arr, low, high):
 pivot = arr[high]
 for i in range(low, high):
 if arr[i] < pivot:
 arr[i], arr[pivot_index] = arr[pivot_index], arr[i]
 return pivot_index
```

This implementation of the quicksort algorithm recursively partitions the input array into two subarrays until it reaches a base case. It uses a while loop to continue sorting the remaining elements until the entire array is sorted.

